Page 3 of 7WPR16FA154
Factual Information
History of Flight
Landing
Landing gear not configured
Approach-VFR go-around
Loss of control in flight (Defining event)
On August 1, 2016, about 1100 Pacific daylight time, an experimental amateur-built Lancair 
360, N528HZ, impacted terrain while landing on runway 31 at Columbia Gorge Regional/The 
Dalles Municipal Airport (DLS), The Dalles, Oregon. The pilot was fatally injured, and the 
airplane was destroyed. The airplane was registered to and operated by the pilot under the 
provisions of 14 
Code of Federal Regulations
 Part 91. Visual meteorological conditions 
prevailed, and no flight plan was filed. The local flight originated from DLS about 1030.
Two witnesses, located on the ramp adjacent to the refueling area, observed the airplane west 
of the runway in a nose-low, steep-left-bank attitude with the left wing pointed directly towards 
the ground. A second later, the airplane impacted the terrain. One witness reported that, 
following the impact, the airplane cartwheeled and slid on its belly before it came to rest.
